04564nam a22006495i 9780520968486DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209684867 a10.1525/97805209684862doi  a(DE-B1597)534802  a(OCoLC)1038025610  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHD9685.P192 7aHIS0190002bisacsh04a333.793/22231 aMeiton, Fredrik, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aElectrical Palestine :bCapital and Technology from Empire to Nation /cFredrik Meiton. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tLists Of Tables And Illustrations -- tAbbreviations And Notes On Sources -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. The Unalterable Order Of Electrical Palestine -- t1. Expert Revolutionary -- t2. Contentious Concession -- t3. The Politics Of Thin Circuitries -- t4. The Radiance of the Jewish National Home -- t5. Industrialization and Revolt -- t6. Electrical Jerusalem -- t7. Statehood and Statelessness -- tConclusion. Electrical Palestine -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aElectricity is an integral part of everyday life—so integral that we rarely think of it as political. In Electrical Palestine, Fredrik Meiton illustrates how political power, just like electrical power, moves through physical materials whose properties govern its flow. At the dawn of the Arab-Israeli conflict, both kinds of power were circulated through the electric grid that was built by the Zionist engineer Pinhas Rutenberg in the period of British rule from 1917 to 1948. Drawing on new sources in Arabic, Hebrew, and several European languages, Electrical Palestine charts a story of rapid and uneven development that was greatly influenced by the electric grid and set the stage for the conflict between Arabs and Jews. Electrification, Meiton shows, was a critical element of Zionist state building. The outcome in 1948, therefore, of Jewish statehood and Palestinian statelessness was the result of a logic that was profoundly conditioned by the power system, a logic that has continued to shape the area until today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aElectrificationxPolitical aspectszPalestine. 0aElectrificationzPalestinexHistoryy20th century. 0aJewish-Arab relations. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCA Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065207908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311066763940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520968486?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520968486423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520968486/original  a978-3-11-061017-8  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-065207-9  UCA Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-066763-9  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2019  aZDB-23-DGGb2019